SIMPLE: triumph
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Triumph
<hw>Tri"umph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>triumphus</ets>, OL. <ets>triumpus</ets>; of uncertain origin; cf.
Gr. <?/ a procession in honor of Bacchus: cf. F. <ets>triomphe</ets>.
Cf. <er>Trump</er> at cards.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld>
<def>A magnificent and imposing ceremonial performed in honor of a
general who had gained a decisive victory over a foreign
enemy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The general was allowed to enter the city crowned with a
wreath of laurel, bearing a scepter in one hand, and a branch of laurel
in the other, riding in a circular chariot, of a peculiar form, drawn by
four horses. He was preceded by the senate and magistrates, musicians,
the spoils, the captives in fetters, etc., and followed by his army on
foot in marching order. The procession advanced in this manner to the
Capitoline Hill, where sacrifices were offered, and victorious commander
entertained with a public feast.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, any triumphal procession; a pompous
exhibition; a stately show or pageant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our daughter,⟦br⟧
In honor of whose birth these <qex>triumphs</qex> are,⟦br⟧
Sits here, like beauty's child.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A state of joy or exultation for success.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great <qex>triumph</qex> and rejoicing was in heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hercules from Spain⟦br⟧
Arrived in <qex>triumph</qex>, from Geryon slain.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Success causing exultation; victory; conquest;
<as>as, the <ex>triumph</ex> of knowledge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A trump card; also, an old game at cards.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Triumph</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Triumph
<hw>Tri"umph</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Triumphed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Triumphing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>triumphare</ets>: cf.
F. <ets>triompher</ets>. See <er>Triumph</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To celebrate victory with pomp; to rejoice over
success; to exult in an advantage gained; to exhibit
exultation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How long shall the wicked <qex>triumph</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xciv. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sorrow on thee and all the pack of you⟦br⟧
That <qex>triumph</qex> thus upon my misery!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To obtain victory; to be successful; to
prevail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Triumphing</qex> over death, and chance, and thee, O
Time.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On this occasion, however, genius triumphed.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be prosperous; to flourish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where commerce <qex>triumphed</qex> on the favoring gales.</q>
<rj><qau>Trumbull.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To play a trump card.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Triumph</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Triumph
<hw>Tri"umph</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To obtain a victory over; to
prevail over; to conquer. Also, to cause to triumph.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two and thirty legions that awe⟦br⟧
All nations of the <qex>triumphed</qex> word.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Triumphal</ent>⟦br⟧
